<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia</i> <i>nova</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>arbuscula</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Echinocactus</i> <i>polycephalus</i>, <i>Echinocereus</i> <i>engelmannii</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> spp., <i>Grayia</i> <i>spinosa</i>, <i>Krascheninnikovia</i> <i>lanata</i>, <i>Lycium</i> <i>andersonii</i>, <i>Menodora</i> <i>spinescens</i>, <i>Mortonia</i> <i>utahensis</i> or <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>osteosperma</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>jeffreyi</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. The herbaceous layer is typically dominated by grasses and forbs such as <i>Blepharipappus</i> <i>scaber</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i> and <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 0.5 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse and/or grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Artemisia nova</i> > 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; no other species with higher cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Artemisia nova</i> is >30% relative cover in the shrub layer with <i>Artemisia arbuscula</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Flats, depressions, rocky slopes and ridges of basalt or limestone. Soils are shallow and poorly drained over bedrock or with clay layer (or caliche) that restricts rooting at depth.  </div>
</div>

        
