<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia nova </i>is a dwarf evergreen shrub with low, spreading branches. The plants are flat-topped and strongly aromatic. It reproduces by light, wind-dispersed seeds.  <i>A. nova </i>may be confused with <i>A. arbuscula </i>when plants lack flowers or fruits, but the dark green glands on the leaf surface are a helpful characteristic for identification. <br/>
<br/>
This shrubland alliance is associated with shallow, rocky soils which experience extreme drought in summer. Soils are typically young, shallow, and coarse-textured. In California, stands of <i>A. nova</i> usually occur on substrates with some calcareous component (Thomas et al. 2004). <i>Artemisia nova</i> dwarf shrublands are the driest habitats of all the <i>Artemisia</i>-dominated alliances. Stands typically grow on well-drained slopes and ridges; often adjacent to other <i>Artemisia</i> spp. Associations on deeper soils. (NatureServe 2019). <br/>
<br/>
Stands in the desert mountains occupy rocky uplands and are usually open, with bare soil between sparse shrubs. Some stands in the San Bernardino Mountains receive sufficient moisture from springs to be seasonally flooded; these areas have high shrub density. In the Modoc region, <i>Artemisia nova</i> is dominant to co-dominant in the shrub layer with <i>A. arbuscula</i> (Boul et al. 2021b). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
