    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Artemisia nova</i> includes the Southern Cascades (M261D), Modoc Plateau (M261G), and the Northwestern Basin and Range (342B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gh, Gm). Stands exist at the western edge of Horse Lake and in the southeastern corner of the Likely Tableland (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Aj, Al). Stands occur on calcareous alluvium in the Clark Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004). They associate with other calciphile alliances dominated by <i>Ephedra funerea, Purshia stansburiana,</i> or <i>Viguiera reticulata.</i> Stands also occur typically on calcareous substrates in the Funeral Mountains (Peterson 1984a, b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dd-f, Dh, Dj). Stands occur in the White Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004). The description of stands in the Lahontan Basin in Nevada (Young et al. 1977) is similar to those in this section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bd). Stands are scattered on lower slopes in the areas of Snowstorm and Shinn Mountains (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands occur typically on calcareous substrates in the Cottonwood,  Last Chance, and Panamint mountains (Peterson 1984a, b), and they are similar to those in the Inyo and White mountains (Peterson 1984a, 1984b, Thomas et al. 2004). They may contain other shrubs, including <i>Atriplex confertifolia</i> and <i>Mortonia utahensis.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bh). Stands in the San Bernardino Mountains in the Big Bear Valley, called pebble plains (Derby and Wilson 1978, 1979, Krantz 1983, 1988), occupy small basins with deep alluvial soils adjacent to vernally moist valley bottoms. They contain <i>Eriogonum kennedyi</i> var. <i>austromontanum, Thelypodium stenopetalum,</i> and other rare (CNPS 1B) species. Adjacent stands have <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> and <i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus.</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia nova </i>is an important browse species for livestock and wildlife, especially during winter months (McMurray 1986). <i>A. nova</i> does not resprout after disturbances. Stands in the San Bernardino National Forest with rare species need continued protection from trampling and grazing.

Fire is uncommon for this alliance, since plants are generally low-growing and widely spaced (NatureServe 2019). The ability of <i>A. nova</i> to sprout following fire events varies among populations, but seeds from unburned plants readily colonize burned areas (McMurray 1986). </div>
</div>

    

    

